data.content:
Here are the improved assertions using MSTest's `CollectionAssert` and more specific `Assert` methods:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0);           // no built-in "not empty", this is fine
    // — or —
    CollectionAssert.That.IsNotEmpty(users);   // if using MSTest v3+

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive))
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);          // null check
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));           // predicate-based — no direct equivalent

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);           // ← much better: shows expected vs actual on failure

    // Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)
    Assert.IsNotNull(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key replacements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, x.Count)` | Shows actual count on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Shows "Expected 3, got 5" instead of just "False" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Clearer intent + better message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(collection contains…)` | `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, item)` | Purpose-built for collections |

Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:
- **`AreEqual`** / **`AreEquivalent`** — same items in same/any order
- **`Contains`** / **`DoesNotContain`**
- **`AllItemsAreUnique`**
- **`IsSubsetOf`**

The biggest win is `Assert.AreEqual` over `Assert.IsTrue` — on failure you get *"Expected: 3, Actual: 5"* instead of just *"Assert.IsTrue failed"*.
